          'Technology companies face a risk landscape shaped by the intangible nature of their products and services. Unlike manufacturers or retailers, tech companies often have minimal physical assets but carry enormous exposure through the software they deploy, the data they process, and the professional services they provide. A bug in your code can cause financial loss for thousands of users simultaneously. A data breach can expose millions of records. An intellectual property dispute can threaten your right to sell the product your entire business is built around.\n\nProfessional liability, often called technology errors and omissions, is the foundational coverage for tech companies. This exposure arises whenever your technology product or service fails to perform as expected or as warranted, causing your client to suffer financial loss. Claims can result from software defects, system downtime, data loss, implementation failures, integration problems, or any other failure in the technology you provide. The contractual environment in technology amplifies this exposure, because enterprise clients typically require service level agreements with financial penalties for non-performance.\n\nCyber liability exposure for technology companies is particularly acute because you are not only protecting your own data but often serving as a custodian of your clients data. A breach at a SaaS provider can expose the data of every customer on the platform. A vulnerability in a managed service provider network can cascade into breaches at every client the MSP serves. Technology companies are both targets for cyberattacks and potential vectors for attacks on their clients, creating a double layer of exposure.',
